    An introduction to `transferUQ` package

    Confidence interval for quantile transfer errors

    qte_interval.Rd

    qte_interval generates one- or two-sided forecast intervals for quantile transfer errors (Section 5.2) with a given coverage level.

    Usage

    qte_interval(
  err,
  coverage,
  side = c("two", "left", "right"),
  betas = seq(0.2, 0.8, 0.01),
  r = NULL
)

    Arguments

    err

    error object; see Details

    coverage

    target coverage level

    side

    "two" for two-sided, "left" for intervals of form \([a, \infty)\), "right" for intervals of form \((-\infty, a]\)

    betas

    a vector of quantiles at which confidence intervals are computed; seq(0.2, 0.8, 0.01) by default

    r

    number of training domains (optional); see Details

    Value

    a data.frame with three columns: beta for the quantile, lb for the lower confidence bound, and ub for the upper confidence bound

    Details

    err should be in one of the following forms.

    • A square asymmetric matrix when the number of training domains \(r = 1\). In this case, err[i, j] records the transfer error using the i-th domain for training and j-th domain for testing.

    • A data.frame with \((r+2)\) columns. The last column records the transfer errors, the second last column records the indices of test domains, and the first r columns record the indices of training domains.

    • (Not recommended) a data.frame with two columns. The second column records the transfer errors and the first column records the indices of test domains.

    For this version, it is recommended to include the transfer errors for all n-choose-(r+1) combinations of training and test domains. Otherwise, ete_interval can still output an interval, though the theoretical guarantee is unclear.

    The input r should be specified only when err is a data.frame with two columns (i.e., without training domain indices).

    Examples

    # Generate an error matrix
n <- 100
set.seed(1)
errmat <- matrix(runif(n^2), nrow = n)
diag(errmat) <- NA

# Generate an error data.frame with r>1
n <- 40
set.seed(1)
idx <- expand.grid(train1 = 1:n, train2 = 1:n, test = 1:n)
idx <- idx[idx$train1 != idx$train2 & idx$train1 != idx$test & idx$train2 != idx$test, ]
err <- cbind(idx, data.frame(val = runif(nrow(idx))))

# Two-sided confidence interval
qte_interval(err, 0.9, "two")
